    "text": "\n# Design concepts\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 021.01.01.01.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.01.01.01.02 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n1.  **021.01.01.01.01** -- Describe the following structural design\n    philosophies:\n    - safe life;\n    - fail-safe (multiple load paths);\n    - damage-tolerant.\n2.  **021.01.01.01.02** -- Explain the purpose of redundancy in aircraft design.\n\n## Summary\n\n### Safe life\n\nIn safe-life design, products are intended to be removed from service at a\nspecific design life.\n\nSafe-life is particularly relevant to simple metal aircraft, where airframe\ncomponents are subjected to alternating loads over the lifetime of the aircraft\nwhich makes them susceptible to metal fatigue. In certain areas such as in wing\nor tail components, structural failure in flight would be catastrophic.\n\n[Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Safe-life_design)\n\n### Fail Safe\n\nIn engineering, a fail-safe is a design feature or practice that in the event of\na specific type of failure, inherently responds in a way that will cause minimal\nor no harm to other equipment, to the environment or to people. Unlike inherent\nsafety to a particular hazard, a system being \"fail-safe\" does not mean that\nfailure is impossible or improbable, but rather that the system's design\nprevents or mitigates unsafe consequences of the system's failure. That is, if\nand when a \"fail-safe\" system fails, it remains at least as safe as it was\nbefore the failure.\n\n[Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fail-safe)\n\n### Damage tolerant\n\nDamage tolerance is a property of a structure relating to its ability to sustain\ndefects safely until repair can be effected. The approach to engineering design\nto account for damage tolerance is based on the assumption that flaws can exist\nin any structure and such flaws propagate with usage.\n\n[Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damage_tolerance)\n\n### Redundancy\n\nRedundancy can be defined as the duplication or triplication of critical\ncomponents or functions of a system with the intention of increasing reliability\nof said system.\n\nKeep this in mind as the definition of redundancy can easily be confused with\nthe definition of Fail safe. Redundancy is a key component of fail-safe\nstructures, but not the only component\n\n<Question id=\"ZRON7SV6I1\" lo={[\"021.01.01.01.01\"]}>\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Which Of these Statements about Structural design principles is correct?\n  </Text>\n  <Text variant=\"oneTwo\">\n    Which Of these Statements about Structural design principles are correct?\n  </Text>\n  <Option correct>Fail Safe implies multiple load Paths</Option>\n  <Option correct>\n    A safe life structure is based on use during a limited time period or number\n    of cycles\n  </Option>\n  <Option correct>\n    Safe life requires a structure to have a minimum stated design life within\n    which no catastrophic damage will occur\n  </Option>\n  <Option>\n    Fail Safe implies the structure will fail, when one component fails\n  </Option>\n  <Option>Safe life is the preferred design technique for aircraft</Option>\n  <Option>\n    Fail-safe structures are preferred to damage tolerant structures as they are\n    lighter due to not requiring extra structural members\n  </Option>\n  <Option>\n    Safe life requires a structure to have a maximum stated design life within\n    which no catastrophic damage will occur\n  </Option>\n\n  <Option>\n    Fail-safe Implies the structure will fail when one component fails\n  </Option>\n</Question>\n",

For example, a maintenance check could include steps to\nvisually inspect for corrosion on specific screw heads, and as soon as it is\ndetected the whole component is replaced.\n\n### Condition monitoring\n\nSimilar to **On Condition maintenance** but leveraging modern day technology to\ncontinuously monitor specific parameters that could indicate failure.\n\n<Question id=\"449I12JXEM\"     "text": "\n# Hydromechanics: basic principles\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **021.03.01.01.01** -- Explain the concept and basic principles of\n    hydromechanics including: hydrostatic pressure; Pascal\"s law; the\n    relationship between pressure, force and area; transmission of power:\n    multiplication of force, decrease of displacement.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 021.03.01.01.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n\n### Pressure\n\n```js\nP = F / A; // (N / m^2 => Pa)\n```\n\nIn Aviation, it's typical to use PSI instead of the SI unit, Pascal.\n\n### Pascal's law\n\n> Pressure in an enclosed container is transmitted equally and undiminished to\n> all parts of the container and acts at right angles to the enclosing walls.\n\nOr, in simpler terms: you can assume that the pressure is constant in the entire\nfluid. That includes the walls. For example:\n\n```\n    F1                             F2\n vvvvvvv                    vvvvvvvvvvvvvvv\n|-------|                  |---------------|\n|   A   |                  |      2A       |\n|       |                  |               |\n|       |__________________|               |\n|                                          |\n|__________________________________________|\n```\n\nAt any surface you can assume that a constant P exists. So you if you know F1\nyou can calculate F2:\n\n```js\nP = F1 / A = F2 / (2 * A)\n\nF2 = (2 * A * F1) / A => F2 = 2 * F1\n```\n\n### Pump Power\n\nA pump deliver a certain mass flow (`m^3 / s`) with a certain Pressure\n(`Pa => N / m^2`). Pump Power can be calculated by multiplying these two values:\n\n```js\nPower = m_flow * P; // `m^3 / s * N / m^2 => (N m) / s => W\n```\n\n<FunctionQuestion variant=\"calculation\" lo=\"021.03.01.01.01\">\n  <Variables\n    variables={{\n    A: [10, 20, 40, 50],\n    B: [5],\n    C: [10, 20, 50, 100]\n    }}\n    answerFunction={(A, B, C) => `${A * B / C}N`}\n  />\n\n  <Text>\n    knowing\n\n    *   F1 = <A /> N\n    *   A = <B /> N\n    *   B = <C /> m^2\n\n    ```\n       F1                             F2\n     vvvvvvv                    vvvvvvvvvvvvvvv\n    |-------|                  |---------------|\n    |   A   |                  |       B       |\n    |       |                  |               |\n    |       |__________________|               |\n    |                                          |\n    |__________________________________________|\n    ```\n\n  </Text>\n</FunctionQuestion>\n",

021.03.02.02.19 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n1.  **021.03.02.02.01** -- Explain the working principle of a hydraulic system.\n2.  **021.03.02.02.02** -- Describe the difference in the principle of operation\n    between a constant pressure system and a system pressurised only on specific\n    demand.\n3.  **021.03.02.02.03** -- State the differences in the principle of operation\n    between a passive hydraulic system (without a pressure pump) and an active\n    hydraulic system (with a pressure pump).\n4.  **021.03.02.02.04** -- List the main advantages and disadvantages of system\n    actuation by hydraulic or purely mechanical means with respect to: weight;\n    size; force.\n5.  **021.03.02.02.05** -- List the main uses of hydraulic systems.\n6.  **021.03.02.02.06** -- State that hydraulic systems can be classified as\n    either high pressure (typically 3000 psi or higher) or low pressure\n    (typically up to 2000 psi).\n7.  **021.03.02.02.07** -- State that a high-pressure hydraulic system is\n    typically operating at 3000 psi but on some aircraft a hydraulic pressure of\n    4000 to 5000 psi may also be used.\n8.  **021.03.02.02.08** -- Explain the working principle of a low-pressure\n    (02000 psi) system.\n9.  **021.03.02.02.09** -- Explain the advantages and disadvantages of a\n    high-pressure system over whose output is dependent on pump revolutions per minute (rpm)\n    (gear type).\n11. **021.03.02.02.11** -- Explain the following different sources of hydraulic\n    pressure, their typical limitations:\n    - manual;\n    - engine;\n    - gearbox;\n    - electrical.\n13. **021.03.02.02.13** -- Describe the working principle and functions of the\n    following hydraulic system components:\n    - reservoir (pressurised and unpressurised);\n    - accumulators;\n    - case drain lines and fluid cooler return lines;\n    - piston actuators (single- and double-acting);\n    - hydraulic motors;\n    - filters;\n    - non-return (check) valves;\n    - relief valves;\n    - restrictor valves;\n    - selector valves (linear and basic rotary selectors, two and four ports);\n    - bypass valves;\n    - shuttle valves;\n    - fire shutoff valves;\n    - priority valves;\n    - fuse valves;\n    - pressure return pipes.\n14. **021.03.02.02.14** -- Explain the function of the demand pump installed on\n    many transport aeroplanes.\n15. **021.03.02.02.15** -- Explain how redundancy is obtained by giving\n    examples.\n16. **021.03.02.02.16** -- Interpret a typical hydraulic system schematic to the\n    level of detail as found in an aircraft flight crew operating manual (FCOM).\n17. **021.03.02.02.17** -- Explain the implication of a high system demand.\n18. **021.03.02.02.18** -- List and describe the instruments and alerts for\n    monitoring a hydraulic system.\n19. **021.03.02.02.19** -- State the indications and explain the implications of\n    the following malfunctions: system leak or low level; low pressure; high\n    temperature.\n\n## Summary\n\n### Components\n\n#### Reservoir\n\nThe reservoir is a tank in which an adequate supply of fluid for the system is\nstored.\n\n#### Accumulator\n\nThe accumulator is a steel sphere divided into two chambers by a synthetic\nrubber diaphragm. The upper chamber contains fluid at system pressure, while the\nlower chamber is charged with nitrogen or air. Cylindrical types are also used\nin high pressure hydraulic systems.\n\nMany aircraft have several accumulators in the hydraulic system. There may be a\nmain system accumulator and an emergency system accumulator. There may also be\nauxiliary accumulators located in various sub-systems.\n\nThe function of an accumulator is to:\n\n- Dampen pressure surges in the hydraulic system caused by actuation of a unit\n  and the effort of the pump to maintain pressure at a preset level.\n- Aid or supplement the power pump when several units are operating at once by\n  supplying extra power from its accumulated, or stored, power.\n- Store power for the limited operation of a hydraulic unit when the pump is not\n  operating.\n- Supply fluid under pressure to compensate for small internal or external (not\n  desired) leaks that would cause the system to cycle continuously by action of\n  the pressure switches continually kicking in.\n\n#### Piston actuator\n\nAn actuating cylinder that transforms energy in the form of fluid pressure into\nmechanical force, or action, to perform work. It is used to impart powered\nlinear motion to some movable object or mechanism.\n\n#### Filter\n\nA filter is a screening or straining device used to clean the hydraulic fluid,\npreventing foreign particles and contaminating substances from remaining in the\nsystem.\n\nIf such objectionable material were not removed, the entire hydraulic system of\nthe aircraft could fail through the breakdown or malfunctioning of a single unit\nof the system.\n\n#### Filter Bypass Valve\n\nFilter modules are often equipped with a bypass relief valve. The bypass relief\nvalve opens if the filter clogs, permitting continued hydraulic flow and\noperation of aircraft systems. Dirty oil is preferred over no flow at all.\nFigure 12-18 shows the principle of operation of a filter bypass valve. The ball\nvalve opens when the filter becomes clogged and the pressure over the filter\nincreases.\n\n#### Non return check valve\n\nA hydraulic or pneumatic system component that allows full flow of fluid in one\ndirection but blocks all flow in the opposite direction.\n\n#### Shuttle Valve\n\nIn certain fluid power systems, the supply of fluid to a subsystem must be from\nmore than one source to meet system requirements.\n\nIn some systems, an emergency system is provided as a source of pressure in the\nevent of normal system failure. The emergency system usually actuates only\nessential components.\n\nThe main purpose of the shuttle valve is to isolate the normal system from an\nalternate or emergency system. It is small and simple; yet, it is a very\nimportant component.\n\n#### Pressure relief valve\n\nHydraulic pressure must be regulated in order to use it to perform the desired\ntasks. A pressure relief valve is used to limit the amount of pressure being\nexerted on a confined liquid. This is necessary to prevent failure of components\nor rupture of hydraulic lines under excessive pressures. The pressure relief\nvalve is, in effect, a system safety valve.\n\n#### Restrictor valve\n\nA fluid power system component that controls the rate of actuator movement by\nrestricting the flow of fluid into or out of the actuator.\n\n#### Priority valve\n\nA priority valve gives priority to the critical hydraulic subsystems over\nnon-critical systems when system pressure is low. For instance, if the pressure\nof the priority valve is set for 2,200 psi, all systems receive pressure when\nthe pressure is above 2,200 psi. If the pressure drops below 2,200 psi, the\npriority valve closes, and no fluid pressure flows to the non-critical systems.\n\n#### Selector Valve\n\nA selector valve is used to control the direction of movement of a hydraulic\nactuating cylinder or similar device. It provides for the simultaneous flow of\nhydraulic fluid both into and out of the unit. Hydraulic system pressure can be\nrouted with the selector valve to operate the unit in either direction and a\ncorresponding return path for the fluid to the reservoir is provided. There are\ntwo main types of selector valves: open-center and closed-center. An open center\nvalve allows a continuous flow of system hydraulic fluid through the valve even\nwhen the selector is not in a position to actuate a unit. A closed-center\nselector valve blocks the flow of fluid through the valve when it is in the\nNEUTRAL or OFF position.\n\n#### Fire shut-off valve\n\nHydraulic shut off valves are usually installed at the engine firewall. In the\nevent of an engine fire, the shut-off valve is closed to prevent possible\nignition of the hydraulic fluid.\n\n#### Hydraulic Fuses\n\nA type of flow control valve that allows a normal flow of fluid in the system\nbut, if the flow rate is excessive, or if too much fluid flows for normal\noperation, the fuse will shut off all further flow.\n\n#### Pressure Return Pipes\n\nPipes that connect \"used\" hydraulic fluid back to the reservoir.\n\n[Source: Faa H-8083-31A Vol 2, Chapter 12](https://www.faa.gov/regulations_policies/handbooks_manuals/aviation/media/amt_airframe_hb_vol_2.pdf)\n\n<Question id=\"HNVH63KULS\" lo={[\"021.03.02.02.13\"]} contentRef=\"### Components\">\n manually/mechanically.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 021.04.01.02.01 | X       | X      |            |             |        |     |         |\n| 021.04.01.02.02 |         |        | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.04.01.02.03 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.04.01.02.04 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.04.01.02.05 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.04.01.02.06 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.04.01.02.07 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.04.01.02.08 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.04.01.02.09 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n\n### 021.04.01.02.01: Landing Gear Components\n\n#### Oleo leg/shock strut;\n\nInside the shock strut...\n\n#### Axles;\n\n#### Bogies and bogie beam;\n\n#### Drag struts;\n\n#### Side stays/struts;\n\n#### Torsion links;\n\n#### Locks (over centre)\n\nWhen the landing gear movement command is issued, the first step in the process\nis to unlock the over centre lock. Then, when reaching the final position,\nanother over-centre mechanism locks the landing gear in place.\n\nFor the \"down lock\", the lock works under spring tension, meaning that hydraulic\nforce must be present to unlock the gear, but not to lock it. In other words,\nthis lock is a bit like any door lock, where you can just push the door to close\nit, but you need to operate a mechanism (the handle) to open it.\n\nFor the \"up lock\", hydraulic pressure is used to maintain the lock state. If the\nhydraulic pressure is removed (intentionally, or in case of failure), the\nlanding gear will be free to operate, and usually fall into the down position.\n\nLanding gear operation is said to be complete, and fully locked once this lock\nis in place.\n\n### 021.04.01.02.05 Operation Lights\n\nLanding gear leavers are accompanied by a set of 2 lights per each landing gear\nunit (typically 3). Each set of lights contains one red, and one green light.\nThere are 3 possible states:\n\n- Green light: Landing gear Down and locked!\n- No light: Landing gear up and locked!\n- Red light: Gear in transfer!\n\nAn aural warning is installed to alert if the plane is at too close to the\nground without having the landing gear extended. This warning usually comes from\nGPWS and says **\"TOO LOW - GEAR\"**.\n\n### 021.04.01.02.06 Ground protection devices\n\nOperating the landing gear on the ground is generally considered a bad idea, so\nmechanisms have been devised to prevent it.\n\nThe first mechanism is known as an **Anti-retract latch**. When the aircraft is\non the ground, its weight compresses the landing gear activating a sensor which\ntrigger a latch mechanism that prevents the landing gear lever from being moved.\nThis latch has an override mechanism in case of a false positive (i.e.: the\nlatch still being active after take off).\n\nAnother mechanism that is commonly used during long stops consists of a safety\npin is inserted into the landing gear lock to prevent operation. These pins must\nbe accompanied by the famous red \"REMOVE BEFORE FLIGHT\" tags.\n\n### 021.04.01.02.07 Limiting Speeds\n\n- V<sub>le</sub> = Maximum speed with landing gear extended\n- V<sub>lo</sub> = Maximum speed with landing gear extended\n\n### 021.04.01.02.09 Emergency Gear extension methods\n\n#### Free Fall\n\nThere are 3 steps in this process:\n\n1.  The cut out valve and the vent vales are released,\n2.  The door up-locks are released (due to the removal of hydraulic pressure)\n3.  The gear locks are released\n\nThis allows the landing gear to fall into position using its own weight. It's\nnot unusual for the emergency checklist to include a step to \"rock your wings\"\nto help with the landing gear movement, and to allows for the down-lock to\nactuate\n\nNote that this system does not rely on hydraulic power to operate. The only\nrequirement is that mechanical power is used to operate the cut out valve\n(usually available in the cockpit).\n\n#### Pneumatic\n\nIn this system a compressed nitrogen bottle is used to force the landing gear\ndown to the locked position. Similar to the free fall procedure, the first step\nis releasing hydraulic pressure in the locks to allow for gear movement. But,\nfor designs where the weight of the gear is not enough, hydrogen is discharged\npushing the gear down. Usually this system will allow to lock the gear down, but\nwon't permit such luxuries as closing the landing gear bay doors.\n\n<Question id=\"MSA1Z4BVY3\" lo=\"021.04.01.02.01\">\n  <Text   "021.07.02": {
    "id": "021.07.02",
    "text": "\n# Ice warning systems: Types, operation, and indications\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 021.07.02.01.01 | X       | X      |            |             |        |     |         |\n| 021.07.02.01.02 | X       | X      |            |             |        |     |         |\n\n1.  **021.07.02.01.01** -- Describe the different operating principles of the\n    following ice detectors:\n    - mechanical systems using air pressure;\n    - electromechanical systems using resonance frequencies.\n2.  **021.07.02.01.02** -- Describe the principle of operation of ice warning\n    systems.\n\n## Summary\n\n### Ice detection systems\n\n#### Pressure differencial system\n\nThis device consists of 2 sets of holes facing the incoming air. One set\ncontains just one large hole, and the second set contains several small holes.\nSummed all together, the small holes have the same area as the large hole.\nBecause of this, under normal conditions, the pressure measured from both sets\nwill be the same, that is, there is 0 pressure differential.\n\nWhen Icing conditions are observed, the slow holes will close much faster than\nthe big hole, generating a pressure differential which can be measured. This\nwill trigger an ice warning light in the cockpit. Eventually, the big hole will\nclose as well, and the pressure differential will be 0. However, this will not\ndismiss the alarm light.\n\nWhen de-icing heating is turned on, the ice will melt much faster on the smaller\nholes, causing, again a pressure differential, but with opposite direction. This\nwill cause the alarm light to be dismissed.\n\n#### Smith's ice detector\n\nThis system uses a vane portruding into the airflow and 2 sets of wholes\ndestributed in front and in the back of the system. When icing conditions\noccour, the front of the vane will freeze first, resulting in negative pressure\non the backside of the probe which triggers a warning light.\n\nRemember, The smiths ice detector is activated by a **decrease in dynamic\npressure**!\n\n#### Electromechanical systems using resonance frequencies (Rosemount ice detector)\n\nThis system consits of a vibrating detector. When there is no icing the detector\nvibrates at a a fixed frequency. When ice starts to accumulate, increasing its\nmass, and reducing the vibration frequency of the detector. This triggers the\nwarning light in the cockpit. A heater is provided for this system in order to\nclear accumulated ice and reset the system.\n\n![Image](images/021.07.02.01-02.png)\n\n#### Hot rod ice detector system\n\nIt consist of a rod placed outside the cockpit in a position that is easely\nobservable from the flight deck. This rod is usally colored matte black so that\nice it can be easily seen when it deposits. A heater is provided to heat the rod\nand clear the ice.\n\n![Image](images/021.07.02.01-01.png)\n\n### Operating principle of ice warning systems\n\n#### Primary automatic\n\nThe ice detector automatically activates ice protection at the optimal moment.\nThis system provides pilots with a system status (active / inactive) and the\nability to manually override.\n\n#### Primary Manual\n\nThe ice detector trigger a warning light, and the crew is responsible for\nactivating the ice protection system\n\n#### Advisory\n\nThe flight crew is responsible for activating the ice protection device based on\nrecommendation of the flight manual. For example, most small aircraft POH's\nrecommend turning the pitot heat on when outside air temperature is less than\n5C, regardless if icing conditions are observed or not. In this system, the ice\ndetector signals are an advisory back up indicator.\n\n<Question id=\"OZJGNF8HJY\" lo=\"021.07.02.01.01\" contentRef=\"#pressure-differential-system\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Which Of these Statements is true regarding differential pressure ice\n    accretion detector?\n  </Text>\n<Text variant=\"multipleCorrect\" select={5}>\n  Which Of these Statements are true regarding differential pressure ice\n  accretion detector?\n</Text>\n<Text variant=\"oneTwo\">\n  Which Of these Statements are true regarding differential pressure ice\n  accretion detector?\n</Text>\n<Option>Large holes freeze first</Option>\n<Option correct>Small holes freeze first</Option>\n<Option correct>Small holes melt first</Option>\n<Option>Small holes are heated first</Option>\n<Option>Small and big holes are heated at the same time</Option>\n<Option correct>\n  An alarm light is activated in the cockpit when a pressure difference is\n  measured between small and big apertures\n</Option>\n\n  <Option>large holes melt first</Option>\n  <Option>The torque of a rotating serrated shat is measured</Option>\n  <Option>It is based on the measurement of temperature and moisture</Option>\n</Question>\n\n<Question\n  id=\"WNR5OTGE1K\"\n  lo=\"021.07.02.01.01\"\n  contentRef=\"#smiths-ice-detector\"\n>\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">What is measured by a Smith ice detector?</Text>\n  <Option>Decrease in static pressure</Option>\n  <Option>Increase in static pressure</Option>\n  <Option correct>Decrease in dynamic pressure</Option>\n  <Option>Increase in dynamic pressure</Option>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id=\"305R40DDBT\" lo=\"021.07.02.01.01\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    What best describes a <Subject />?\n  </Text>\n<Option subject={[[\"Pressure differential system\"]]}>\n  The total pressure measured at set of small holes is compared against one\n  large hole of equal area. When icing conditions are observed, a pressure\n  differential between the 2 sets can be measured.\n</Option>\n<Option subject={[[\"Smith ice detector\"]]}>\n  A vane portudring to the airflow has holes in front and the back. When icing\n  conditions are observed, the holes in front of the vane become blocked\n  resulting in a pressure deferencial which can be measured.\n</Option>\n<Option subject={[[\"Rosemount ice detector\"]]}>\n  A vibrating rod is placed onto the incoming airflow. When icing conditions are\n  observed the vibration frequency is reduced resulting in an alarm light in the\n  cockpit\n</Option>\n\n  <Option subject={[[\"Hot rod ice detector\"]]}>\n    A rod is installed in a position easily visible from the cokpit and provided\n    with a flood light. Flight deck crew can use it to visually observe the\n    accumulation of ice.\n  </Option>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id=\"K7R2PLJJ2X\" lo=\"021.07.02.01.02\" contentRef=\"### Ice detection systems\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    How does the <Subject /> ice detection system operate?\n  </Text>\n<Option subject={[[\"advisory\"]]}>\n  The flight crew activates the ice protection system based on Flight manual\n  recommendations, such as outside air temperature, and moisture. temperature, of\n    both battery and environment; physical condition of the battery; battery\n    charging.\n10. **021.09.02.01.10** -- Describe how to contain a battery thermal runaway\n    highlighting the following: how one cell can affect the neighbouring cells;\n    challenges if it happens in an aircraft during flight.\n\n## Summary\n\nAn electric battery is a source of electric power consisting of one or more\nelectrochemical cells with external connections for powering electrical devices.\n\nWhen a battery is supplying electric power, its positive terminal is the cathode\nand its negative terminal is the anode. The terminal marked negative is the\nsource of electrons that will flow through an external electric circuit to the\npositive terminal.\n\nWhen a battery is connected to an external electric load, a redox reaction\nconverts high-energy reactants to lower-energy products, and the free-energy\ndifference is delivered to the external circuit as electrical energy.\nHistorically the term \"battery\" specifically referred to a device composed of\nmultiple cells; however, the usage has evolved to include devices composed of a\nsingle cell.\n\n[Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_battery)\n\nSince battery cells are able to produce relatively low voltage, they are placed\nin series to achieve higher voltage levels. This means that\n\n**if one cell fails, the entire battery is rendered inoperative**\n\n|                          | lead-acid     | nickel-cadmium                     | lithium-ion | lithium-polymer |\n| ------------------------ | ------------- | ---------------------------------- | ----------- | --------------- |\n| Electrolyte              | Sulfuric acid | 70% water / 30% potassium peroxide | --          | --              |\n| Nominal voltage per cell | 2 - 2.2v      | 1.2v - 1.25v                       | --          | --              |\n| Load behaviour           |               |                                    |             |                 |\n| Charging characteristics |               |                                    |             |                 |\n| Risk of Thermal runaway  |               |                                    |             |                 |\n\n### Thermal runaway\n\nGenerally, charging a battery will cause it to heat up. Think about how warm an\nolder phone can get get as it charging. However this heating up is kept in check\nas long as the current being sent to the battery is within limits.\n\nThermal runaway occurs when over charging of a battery takes place. Under these\ncircumstances, battery temperature quickly increases, increasing the rate of the\nchemical transformations occurring within a cell which leads to even more\nheating, leading to a vicious cycle. Eventually, the electrolyte will boil\nresulting in a fire or explosion.\n\nThermal runaway can be prevented by monitoring battery temperature, and stopping\nto charge if the temperature gets too high.\n\n<Question id=\"4J6ODTINMG\" lo=\"021.09.02.01.03\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    The voltage of a fully charged <Subject /> is approximately\n  </Text>\n\n  <Option subject={[[\"lead-acid battery\"]]}>2.2v</Option>\n  <Option subject={[[\"nickel-cadmium battery\"]]}>1.25V</Option>\n  <Option>1.5V</Option>\n  <Option>3.2V</Option>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id=\"X70ITOG264\" lo=\"021.09.02.01.03\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Why are the batteries used in modern aircraft of the nickel-cadmium type?\n  </Text>\n<Text variant=\"multipleCorrect\" select={6}>\n  Which of these statements best describe the nickel-cadmium batteries used in\n  modern aircraft?\n</Text>\n<Option why=\"Thermal runaway is much more likely in NiCa batteries and require more expensive and complex controllers than Lead-acid batteries\">\n  Low risk of thermal runaway\n</Option>\n<Option why=\"This is just wrong from a physics point of view. All ideal cycles consist of 4\nsteps, usually in a cyclic sequence of Compression -> Combustion -> Expansion ->\nCooling.\n\n![Brayton ideal cycle](images/021.11.01.2-02.png)\n\nThis ideal cycle is however drastically different from a real cycle.\n\n- The cooling part of an ideal cycle does not really exist in a real engine.\n  After the the expansion stage the air is released onto the atmosphere\n- In the ideal Brayton cycle the energy used in the combustion is the same\n  energy that is recouped by the cooling process.\n- In the ideal Brayton cycle the only source of power results from the\n  difference between the power required at the compressor and the power\n  available in the turbine.\n\nThat being said, what makes the brayton cycle unique, and different from Diesel\nand otto cycle, is that combustion is done at constant pressure (and not\nconstant volume).\n\n### Free Power Turbine\n\n> A free-turbine turboshaft is a form of turboshaft or turboprop gas turbine\n> engine where the power is extracted from the exhaust stream of a gas turbine\n> by an independent turbine, downstream of the gas turbine. The power turbine is\n> not mechanically connected to the turbines that drive the compressors, hence\n> the term \"free\", referring to the independence of the power output shaft (or\n> spool). This is opposed to the power being extracted from the\n> turbine/compressor shaft via a gearbox.\n\n![Free Power turbine](images/021.11.01.2-01.png)\n\n[Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free-turbine_turboshaft)\n\n<Question id=\"EZZV2N5LJ0\" lo=\"021.11.01.02.09\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneTwo\">\n    which | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n\n### Compressor stall and Surge\n\nCompressor blades are aerofoils, and if a too high angle of attack exists\nbetween the blade and the incoming airflow a stall will occur. When such a stall\noccurs over one blade, or a limited number of blades we are in the presence of a\n_Compressor Stall_.\n\nCompressor stalls always begins at the first stages of a compressor and travel\ndeeper and deeper into to the turbine as they develop. If the entire compressor\nis stalled, we are in the presence of a _Compressor Surge_. When a compressor\nsurge develops, Velocity decreases inside the compressor and conversely static\npressure rapidly increases. This will eventually lead to a flow reversal which\nin turn will _choke_ the combustion chambers and lead to a flame-out.\n\nCompressor stall and surge are more common when the engine is at low RPMs\n\n<Question id=\"YVGGRRTEBH\" lo={[\"021.11.02.02.09\", \"021.11.02.04.09\"]}>\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Which of the following statements are true regarding the flow in a\n    <Subject /> subsonic gas turbine engine intake?\n  </Text>\n<Option\n  subject={[[\"convergent\"]]}\n  why=\"If the cross sectional area is decreasing, and mass flow is assumed constant, the average speed of the flow must be assumed to increase. CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 021.11.02.04.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.02 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.03 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.04 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.05 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.06 | X       | X      |            |             |        |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.07 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.08 | X       | X      |            |             |        |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.09 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.02.04.10 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n\n### Impulse and Reaction turbines\n\nThe idea behind a turbine is to extract energy from the incoming flow to convert\nit into rotation of a turbine wheel. In principle, there are two ways to achieve\nthis.\n\n![Reaction vs Impulse turbines](images/021.11.02.04-01.jpeg)\n\n#### Impulse turbine\n\nIn an impulse turbine, the basic idea is to have the incoming jet of air strike\nthe rotor blades, causing them to move. This process extracts kinetic energy\nfrom the incoming airflow and as such results in a velocity drop of the flow in\nthe rotor. Pressure on the other hand, remains constant in this process.\n\nThe guiding vanes in an impulse turbine are used to optimize flow direction so\nas to strike the rotor blades at the optimal position. They are also used to\naccelerate the flow by converting potential energy into kinetic energy,\nresulting in a pressure decrease, and a velocity increase.\n\n#### Reaction turbine\n\nIn a reaction turbine, the disk is rotated as a consequence of the aerodynamic\naction of the air passing through the rotor blades. Rotor blades are shaped like\naerofoils and function very much like one. As the flow develops around an\naerofoil. flow velocity as a tendency to increase and pressure decreases.\nFurthermore, there is usually slight convergence of the rotor blades duct,\nfurther promoting the increase in speed and a decrease in velocity.\n\nThe function of Nozzle guide vanes in a reaction turbine are subject of much\ndebate. Primary sources, contradict each other.\n\nAccording to [Rolls Royce - The Jet Engine; Chapter 5]():\n\n> In the reaction type the fixed nozzle guide vanes are designed to alter the\n> gas flow direction without changing the pressure.\n\nBut according to\n[Aviation Maintenance Technician Handbook Powerplant, Volume 1]()\n\n> the nozzle converts a varying portion of the heat and pressure energy to\n> velocity energy that can then be converted to mechanical energy through the\n> turbine blades.\n\nEASA considers the second source as correct. For both impulse and reaction\nturbines the same effect from a nozzle guide canes is to be expected; As no\nenergy is absorbed, we observe a pure exchange of kinetic and potential energy.\nTotal Energy remains constant, but pressure decreases and velocity increases.\n\n![Reaction Turbine](images/021.11.02.04-02.jpeg)\n\n#### In summary\n\n- P - Flow static Pressure\n- T - Flow static Temperature\n- V - Flow velocity\n- E - Flow total energy - Kinetic Energy (from its velocity) + Potential Energy\n  (from its pressure)\n\n|                     | Impulse Turbine | Reaction Turbine |\n| ------------------- | --------------- | ---------------- |\n| P/T at Stator Vanes | Decreases       | Decreases        |\n| V at Stator Vanes   | Increases       | Increases        |\n| E at Stator Vanes   | Constant        | Constant         |\n|                     |                 |                  |\n| P/T at Rotor blades | Constant        | Decreases        |\n| V at Rotor blades   | Decreases       | Decreases        |\n| E at Rotor blades   | Decreases       | Decreases        |\n\n**Remember**:\n\n- Pressure and Temperature both represent potential energy of the flow and as\n  such follow the same pattern.\n- Total energy remains constant In stator stages, and decreases in rotor stages\n  as energy is absorbed.\n- In stator stages the flows is redirected and/or constricted resulting in an\n  exchange of potential for kinetic energy\n- In rotor stages energy is absorbed resulting in a net less of kinetic +\n  potential energy.\n- In an impulse type turbine, at the rotor only kinetic energy is absorbed.\n  Pressure remains constant and velocity decreases.\n- In an reaction type turbine, at the rotor both kinetic and potential energy\n  are absorbed. Both Pressure and Velocity decrease.\n\n<Question id=\"0POEPVQ0TV\" lo={[\"021.11.02.04.02\"]} contentRef=\"### Impulse and Reaction turbines\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Which of these | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.04.01.14 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.04.01.15 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.04.01.16 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 021.11.04.01.17 | X       | X      | X          | ratings:\n    take-off; go-around; maximum continuous thrust/power; maximum climb\n    thrust/power.\n2.  **021.11.04.01.02** -- Explain spool-up time.\n3.  **021.11.04.01.03** -- Explain the reason for the difference between ground\n    and approach flight idle values (rpm).\n4.  **021.11.04.01.04** -- State the parameters that can be used for setting and\n    monitoring the thrust/power.\n5.  **021.11.04.01.05** -- Describe the terms \"alpha range\", \"beta range\" and\n    \"reverse thrust\" as applied to a turboprop power lever.\n6.  **021.11.04.01.06** -- Explain the dangers of inadvertent beta-range\n    selection in flight for a turboprop.\n7.  **021.11.04.01.07** -- Explain the purpose of engine trending.\n8.  **021.11.04.01.08** -- Explain how the exhaust gas temperature is used to\n    monitor turbine stress.\n9.  **021.11.04.01.09** -- Describe the effect of engine acceleration and\n    deceleration on the EGT.\n10. **021.11.04.01.10** -- Describe the possible limitations on the use of the\n    thrust-reverser system at low forward speed.\n13. **021.11.04.01.13** -- Explain the term \"engine seizure\".\n14. **021.11.04.01.14** -- State the possible causes of engine seizure and\n    explain their preventative measures.\n15. **021.11.04.01.15** -- Describe the potential consequences of a leak in the\n    following two designs of fuel and oil heat exchanger: oil pressure higher\n    than fuel pressure with oil leaking into the fuel system, potentially\n    affecting the combustion and running of the engine; fuel pressure higher\n    than oil pressure with fuel leaking into the oil system, potentially\n    increasing the risk of a fire due to fuel entering warm parts of the engine\n    that should be free from fuel.\n16. **021.11.04.01.16** -- Explain oil-filter clogging (blockage) and the\n    implications for the lubrication system.\n17. **021.11.04.01.17** -- Give examples of monitoring instruments of an engine.\n18. **021.11.04.01.18** -- Describe how to identify and assess engine damage\n    based on instrument indications.\n\n## Summary\n\n### Engine Ratings\n\nTake off\n\nGo around\n\nMaximum continuos power / thrust\n\nmaximum climb power / thrust\n\n### Spool up\n\n### Flight Idle and Ground Idle.\n\nTurbine engines reaction times can be quite slow as the turbine and compressor\nhave to accelerate to obtain the power level requested when moving the power\nlever. The slowest response time happens when the engine is on idle, and the\nabsolute worst scenario is increasing from idle to full power.\n\nBecause of this, flight idle power is significantly higher than ground idle\npower; So that Go around power can be obtain with minimum delay. Ground power\nidle is usually the minimum power required to maintain engine combustion.\n\n### Alpha Range vs Beta Range and Reverse Thrust\n\nSome turbo propellers have two operating ranges for their engines. An **alpha\nrange** intended for flight, and a **beta range** intended for ground\noperations.\n\nInside the **alpha range** engine operation is as you would expect from a\nConstant Speed propeller aircraft: The Engine Power is controlled by the Power\nlever, and the propeller RPM by the Pitch Lever.\n\nWhen decreasing the power below idle power, the **beta range** is entered. Here,\nthe power lever controls blade pitch directly, and Torque is kept at Idle. When\nlanding, the pitch angle of the blades will be smaller than the angle of\nincoming air, effectively giving the propeller a negative angle of attack,\nresulting in reverse thrust being generated.\n\nIn some aircraft it's possible to decrease the blade pitch onto negative angles\nto produce **reverse thrust** that can be used to move the aircraft backwards.\nIn this regime, the power lever controls both pitch angle and power lever\n\nNeedless to say, entering the beta range in flight conditions is a terrible idea\n;).\n\nIn Summary:\n\n|         | Power lever                                    | Prop Lever        | Torque   | Thrust             |\n| ------- | ---------------------------------------------- | ----------------- | -------- | ------------------ |\n| Alpha   | Controls Engine Torque                         | Controls prop RPM | Positive | Positive           |\n| Beta    | Controls Prop Pitch                            | ---               | IDLE     | Postive / negative |\n| Reverse | Controls Negative Prop Pitch and Engine Torque | ---               | Positive | Negative           |\n\n[Source](https://skybrary.aero/articles/beta-range)\n[Source](https://skybrary.aero/articles/alpha-range)\n\n### Monitoring instruments of an engine.\n\n### Exhaust Gas temperature (EGT)\n\nEGT is a critical parameter that, in normal conditions, correlates directly with\nengine power. The higher the power setting, the higher the EGT. EGT is typically\nmeasured on the HP turbine outlet.\n\n### Engine Pressure Ratio (EPR)\n\nRatio of pressure of the turbine output / pressure of the compressor input.\nEffectively indicates the thrust of a turbofan engine.\n\n### N1\n\nShows RPM of the fan and low pressure compressor. Effectively, indicates the\nthrust of a turbofan engine.\n\n### N2\n\n### Vibration sensors\n\nused to detect imbalance of one or both of the spools. These imbalances are\nusually a sign of damage in the compressor or turbine blades which tend to\ndevelop rapidly into a critical failure.\n\n### Engine Trending\n\nEngine Trend Analysis is a method of assessing the health of an engine over\ntime. This allows to enhance maintenance planning and detect anomalies. For\nexample, An engine operating limits may set the normal operating range of oil\ntemperatures between 65 and 95, but when monitoring the trend of a specific\nengine it is verified the normal operating engine is below 70 over 99.5% of the\ntime. in this scenario an operating speed of 75 may be sufficient to trigger an\ninvestigation of engine condition since despite being within limits, something\nmay be off.\n",

  "021.11.04.02": {
    "id": "021.11.04.02",
    "text": "\n# Starting malfunctions\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 021.11.04.02.01 | X       | X      |            |             |        |     |         |\n| 021.11.04.02.02 |         |        | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n1.  **021.11.04.02.01** -- Describe the indications and the possible causes of\n    the following aeroplane starting malfunctions: false (dry or wet) start;\n    tailpipe fire (torching); hot start; abortive (hung) start; no N1 rotation;\n    no FADEC indications.\n2.  **021.11.04.02.02** -- Describe the indications and the possible causes of\n    the following helicopter starting malfunctions: false (dry or wet) start;\n    tailpipe fire (torching); hot start; abortive (hung) start; no N1 rotation;\n    freewheel failure; no FADEC indications.\n\n## Summary\n\n### Tailpipe fire (torching)\n\nAn ignition of fuel that has previously puddled in the the turbine casing or\nexhaust section. One of the most common scenarios for this to happen is after a\nfailed start attempt.\n\nWhen this event occours a visible flame can be seen escaping from the exhaust\npipe. entering will increase but an engine fire warning is not triggered.\n\n### Hot start\n\n**NOTE: Hot start for turbine and piston engines are different phenomena**\n\nHot start is caused by improper start technique. When starting a jet engine, the\ncompressor is spooled up to generate enough cooling flow around the combustion\nchamber, before ignition is attempted.\n\nIncorrect fuel scheduling, i.e.: starting ignition too soon, can cause a hot\nstart since there is not enough cooling flow to keep the combustion stable.\nTemperature in the combustion chamber will increase rapidly leading to damage.\n\nAnother cause pilot's should be aware for hot starts, is starting the engine\nwith a strong tail wind. The wind will reduce the amount of air flow around the\ncombustion chamber potentially leading to a hot start.\n\n[Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hot_start)\n\n### Abortive (hung) start\n\n### No N1 rotation\n\n### Freewheel failure\n\n### No FADEC indications\n\n<Question id=\"4I52DMOX7R\" lo=\"021.11.04.02.01\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Name the possible cause and indications of a <Subject />.\n  </Text>\n<Option subject={[[\"tailpipe fire\"]]}>\n  Fuel that has puddled in the turbine casing or exhaust during start-up may\n  ignite. V_{aircraft}) \\;[N]\n$$\n\nThrust is the mass flow of hot gas ($kg/s$) times the difference between the\nexhaust velocity and the aircraft velocity ($m/s$).\n\nAs altitude increases, air density decreases. As a consequence of this the mass\nflow of hot gas decreases. The maximum velocity of the exhaust flow however\nremains unchanged. Therefore, **As altitude increases, maximum thrust\ndecreases**.\n\nFor Specific Fuel Consumption, remember the following formula:\n\n$$\nSFC = \\frac{\\dot{m}_{fuel}}{Power}\n      \\;\\; \\left[ \\frac{kg \\cdot s^{-1}}{N s^{-1}} \\right]\n    = \\frac{m_{fuel}}{Thrust}\n      \\;\\; \\left[ \\frac{kg}{N} \\right]\n$$\n\n**Remember**: Specific Fuel consumption is the amount of fuel consumed per unit\nthrust.\n\nWe saw before that maximum thrust is decreasing with increasing altitude.\nHowever, Fuel Consumption also decreases with increasing altitude. As less air\nis flowing through the jet (decreasing $\\dot{m}_{jet}$) less fuel needs to be\ncombusted as engines operate at a constant fuel/air ratio.\n\nAt the end of the day you just have to memorize that the decrease in fuel\nconsumption is superior to the decrease of thrust. This is howeve quite easy to\nremember. Jets like to fly as high as possible to save as much fuel as possible.\nThis is because **flying at higher altitudes decreases the SFC**.\n\nVariations of **SFC** and maximum **T** with airspeed are much simpler to reason\nwith.\n\nLooking back to the formula $$T = \\dot{m}_{jet}(V_{jet} - V_{aircraft})$$, in an\nextreme case where the aeroplane speed catches up with the jet exhaust speed,\nThrust is zero. In reverse if the aeroplane is stationary Thrust is maximum.\n\nSFC follows a similar pattern: The faster you go the more fuel you spend and the\nleast amount of power you produce. **Keep in mind that is an analysis of the\nengine SFC, not the aircraft!** Aerodynamic effects, that cause a parabolic\nlooking curve for SFC are not considered here. \\*\\*SFC is minimum with zero\nspeed and increases to infinity as TAS increases.\n\n<Question\n  id=\"I9V962NGD7\"\n  lo={[\"021.11.05.01.01\", \"021.11.05.01.02\"]}\n  contentRef=\"### Thrust and SFC variations with altitude and TAS\"\n>\n  <Text Similarly, APUs are usually started by a flick of a switch.\n\nSince the APU primary role is to supply electrical power, its setup is\nsignificantly simpler than the one for main engines, mostly because there is no\nneed for a Constant Speed Drive: the APU already operates at a constant speed.\nHowever, because of this it's not possible to run this generator in parallel\nwith the main engine generators. As such, when selecting the APU as a power\nsource, the other sources are disconnected. Regardless, as all other generators,\nthe APU supplies power in three-phase, 115-120V, 400Hz AC.\n\nAPUS must be equipped with an automatic shutdown protection system that\nactivates when:\n\n- EGT limit is exceeded,\n- APU Fire\n- Low oil pressure\n- High oil temperature\n\nIn any engine, Low oil pressure typically indicates a leak, which will\neventually result in either overheating or not enough lubrication causing\nmechanical damage. High oil pressure is usually not problematic and is kept in\ncheck by pressure release valves.\n\nRemember: `High Temperature and Low Pressure => BAD!`.\n\n<Question id=\"LFS7CP9SL2\" Summary\n\n<Question id=\"LO9IT60XU9\" lo={[\"022.02.01.02.02\"]}>\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    If the <Subject /> the instrument will:\n  </Text>\n<Option>gradually indicate zero</Option>\n<Option>\n  indicate a height equivalent to the setting on the millibar subscale\n</Option>\n<Option\n  subject={[\n    [\n      \"static source to an airspeed indicator (ASI) becomes blocked during a climb\",\n    ],\n  ]}\n>\n  under-read\n</Option>\n<Option\n  subject={[\n    [\n      \"static source to an airspeed indicator (ASI) becomes blocked during a descent\",\n    ],\n  ]}\n>\n  over-read\n</Option>\n<Option\n  subject={[\n    [\"static source of an altimeter becomes blocked during a descent\"],\n    [\"static source of an altimeter becomes blocked during a climb\"],\n  ]}\n>\n  continue to display the reading at which the blockage occurred\n</Option>\n\n  <Explanation>\n    The altimeter's only input source is static pressure.\n    If this becomes blocked, the instrument will simply 'freeze',\n    indicating the altitude at which the blockage occurred.\n\n    The Airspeed indicator has 2 inputs: The pitot tube and the static port.\n    Velocity is computed from the difference between the total pressure and the\n    static pressure. The higher the difference, the higher the speed.\n\n    When the static port becomes blocked, the base value for this comparison\n    stagnates.\n\n    In case of a climb, the outside air pressure will be decreasing, while our\n    instrument will be measuring a value that is higher than the real value. The\n    total pressure pressure will also be decreasing, meaning that our instrument\n    will begin to under read the velocity.\n\n    The opposite is true during a descent where the static port will be\n    under-reading the static pressure, but the dynamic pressure will keep\n    increasing, leading to an over-read of the velocity.\n\n  </Explanation>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id=\"5REZVKTC16\" lo={[\"\"]}>\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    The error in altimeter readings caused by the variation of the static\n    pressure near the source is known as:\n  </Text>\n\n  <Option>barometric error.</Option>\n  <Option correct>position pressure error</Option>\n  <Option>hysteresis effect.</Option>\n  <Option>instrument error.</Option>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id=\"T0PKBXH2IO\" lo={[\"\"]}>\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    When flying in <Subject />, the altimeter will:\n  </Text>\n<Option subject={[[\"warm air (warm than standard atmosphere)\"]]}>\n  underestimate\n</Option>\n<Option>be just as correct as before</Option>\n<Option subject={[[\"cold air (colder than standard atmosphere)\"]]}>\n  overestimate\n</Option>\n<Option>show the actual height above ground</Option>\n\n  <Explanation>\n    > From High to low, beware below! From Hot to cold, don't be bold!\n  </Explanation>\n</Question>\n",

glideslope\n    (G/S).\n7.  **022.06.02.01.07** -- Describe how the autopilot uses speed, aircraft\n    configuration or flight phase as a measure for the magnitude of control\n    inputs and how this may affect precision and stability.\n8.  **022.06.02.01.08** -- Explain the following mixed modes: take-off;\n    go-around; approach (APP).\n9.  **022.06.02.01.09** -- Describe the two types of autopilot configurations\n    and explain the implications to the pilot for either and when comparing the\n    two principles: flight-deck controls move with the control surface when the\n    autopilot is engaged; autopilot\n    servos/actuators reconnect when TCS button is released and the autopilot\n    returns to previously engaged mode(s).\n15. **022.06.02.01.15** -- Explain that only one autopilot may be engaged at any\n    time except for when APP is armed in order to facilitate a fail-operational\n    autoland.\n16. **022.06.02.01.16** -- Explain the difference between an armed and an\n    engaged mode: not all modes have an armed state available; a mode will only\n    become armed if certain criteria are met; an armed mode will become engaged\n    (replacing the previously engaged mode, if any) when certain criteria are\n    met.\n17. **022.06.02.01.17** -- Describe the sequence of events when a mode is\n    engaged and the different phases: initial phase where attitude is changed to\n    obtain a new trajectory in order to achieve the new parameter; the\n    trajectory will be based on rate of closure which is again based on the\n    difference between the original parameter and the new parameter; capture\n    phase where the aircraft will follow a predefined rate of change of\n    trajectory to achieve the new parameter without overshooting/ undershooting;\n    tracking or hold phase where the aircraft will maintain the set parameter\n    until a new change has been initiated.\n18. **022.06.02.01.18** -- Explain automatic mode reversion and typical\n    situations where it may occur: no suitable data for the current mode such as\n    flight plan discontinuity when in LNAV/managed NAV; proximate intruders; traffic advisory (TA); resolution advisory\n    (RA).\n5.  **022.12.10.01.05** -- State that ACAS II will issue commands in the\n    vertical plane only (climb, descent or maintain), and that the commands are\n    complied with as a manual manoeuvre.\n6.  **022.12.10.01.06** -- Explain that an RA may or may not require any active\n    control input and the implications of reacting instinctively without\n    awareness of actual control inputs required to comply with the RA.\n7.  **022.12.10.01.07** -- Explain that if two aircraft are fitted with ACAS II,\n    the RA will be coordinated.\n8.  **022.12.10.01.08** -- State that ACAS II equipment can take into account\n    several threats simultaneously.\n9.  **022.12.10.01.09** -- State that a detected aircraft without\n    altitude-reporting can only generate a TA;     "id": "061.01.04.02",
    "text": "\n# Units\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1. **061.01.04.02.01** -- Convert between units of distance (nautical mile (NM),\n   kilometre (km), statute mile (SM), feet (ft), inches (in)).\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 061.01.04.02.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n\nThere are three ways of doing this. All of them are equally valid, and we\nrecommend you mastering the 3 of them. Practice makes perfect. Make sure to try\nall of these approaches to answer questions until you can use either of them in\nan almost automated way.\n\n#### Precise conversions.\n\n- 1 NM = 1.852 km\n- 1 SM = 1.609 km\n- 1 m = 3.28 ft\n- 1 ft = 12 inches\n\n### Approximations.\n\nIf you are not a fan of mental arithemetics or convoluted menemonics you can\nconsider skipping this method and focusing on memorizing the other 2 methods.\n\nThere are several \"rule of thumb\" approximations for these conversations. These\nare usually good enough for you to exclude wrong answers immediatly simply\nbecause they are not even close to the correct answer. Knowing these is also\ngreat if you find yourself in the cockpit and need to do some rough estimations.\n\n#### NM <=> km\n\n> Multiply by 2 and reduce 10%\n\ni.e.: **5 NM**, you multiply by 2 and get **10**. **10%** of 10 is **1**.\n**10 - 1 = 9**. 5 NM is about 9 km. (precise answer: 9.26)\n\nYou can reverse this operation for the opposite conversion:\n\ni.e.: **7km**, you sum 10%, to get about **8**, devide by 2 and you get **4**. 7\nkm is about 4NM (precise answer: 3.78).\n\nAs an even rougher estimation, remember that **1 NM is slightly less than 2\nkm**.\n\n### ft to meter\n\n> 3 is 1, 6 is 2, 10 is 3\n\n- **3000 ft = 1000m**, This is the basic idea. you simplify that 1m = 3ft\n- **6000 ft = 2000m**, you keep the simplication: 1m = 3ft\n- **10000 ft = 3000m**, Instead of increasing 1000m at 90000ft you \"wait\" for\n  10.000ft.\n\nFor more complex operations you just split the distance in blocks of \"3 and 10\".\nAnd then add some \"magic poweder\" to compensate for the remainer:\n\n- **27.000ft = 2 \\* 10.000 + 6.000 + something = 6000m + 2000m + something =\n  8500m**,\n\nThis approximation still works the other way around, but the head arithmatics\nare a bit more convoluted.\n\n- **1000 meters = 3000ft**, You multiply by 3. (Correct: 3280)\n- **2000 meters = 6000ft**, You multiply by 3. (Correct: 6562)\n- **3000 meters = 10.000ft**, You multiply by 3 again, but since its the third\n  time you add 1000. (9842m)\n- **7000 meters = 10.000 ft + 10.000ft + 3.000ft = 23.000ft**, Every 3000 m are\n  10.000 ft, and the last 1000m is only \"3000ft\"\n\n### Flight Computer\n",

It' just a \"rule of thumb\"\n    approximation you can use for doing quick arethemetics inside a cockpit. These values are just\n    pulled straight from EASA Learning Objectives and you should memorize them:\n\n    *   Average TAS used for climb problems is calculated at the altitude 2/3 of the\n        cruising altitude.\n    *   Average TAS used for descent problems is calculated at the altitude 1/2 of the\n        descent altitude.\n\n    This makes some sense as a descent will usually be performed at a constant\n    descent rate throughout, making the middle point a decent average of the wind\n    speed and direction. During a climb however, you can assume a climb rate\n    decrease towards the end of the climb, biassing the \"average\" point towards a\n    higher altitude. As such a higher factor of 2/3 is used.\n\n  </Explanation>\n</Question>\n",

    "text": "\n# Local Mean Time (LMT)\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **061.05.01.01.01** -- Explain the concepts of a mean solar day and LMT.\n2.  **061.05.01.02.01** -- Perform LMT and UTC calculations.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 061.05.01.01.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 061.05.01.02.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n\n### Mean solar day\n\nMean solar time is the hour angle of the mean Sun plus 12 hours. This 12 hour\noffset comes from the decision to make each day start at midnight for civil\npurposes, whereas the hour angle or the mean sun is measured from the local\nmeridian.\n\n[Source: Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_time#Mean_solar_time)\n\n### Local Mean Time\n\nLocal mean time is a form of solar time that corrects the variations of local\napparent time, forming a uniform time scale at a specific longitude. This\nmeasurement of time was used for everyday use during the 19th century before\ntime zones were introduced beginning in the late 19th century; it still has some\nuses in astronomy and navigation.\n\n[Source: Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_mean_time)\n\nIn simpler words: LMT is the mean time of the specific longitude you are\ncurrently at. If you found yourself in Greenwish at 0 West during the winter,\nthe LMT would coincide with the time in your clock. But if you were to move 3\nWest, the LMT would be $$3\\deg / 15\\deg \\times 60 = 12 minutes$$ ahead of time\n(your watch would indicate 12:00, but LMT is 12:12).\n\nLocal Mean time advances consitently with longitude at a rate of 15 per hour\n(**remember** 360 = 24 hours).\n\n<Question id=\"3VBA5NI940\" lo={[\"061.05.01.01.01\"]} contentRef=\"### Local Mean Time\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    At <Subject /> Local Mean Time of an observer...\n  </Text>\n<Option\n  subject={[[\"0000\"]]}\n  why=\"The local mean time counts time from the anti-meridian. As such, hour 12:00 corresponds to the meridian\"\n>\n  The mean sun is in transit with the observer meridian\n</Option>\n<Option why=\"Local mean time awlays refers to the &#x22;mean sun&#x22;.\">\n  The apparent sun is in transit wit the observer anti-meridian\n</Option>\n\n  <Option why=\"Local mean time awlays refers to the &#x22;mean sun&#x22;.\">\n    The apparent sun is in transit wit the observer meridian\n  </Option>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id=\"3VBA5NI943\" id=\"nhdaHnfa12\" lo={['061.05.01.01.01', '061.05.02.01.01', '061.05.01.02.01']}>\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    When proceeding, on a given date, along a parallel towards the east, the moment of sunrise will\n    occur one hour early every 15 deifference in logitutude whn time is expressed in...\n  </Text>\n<Option\n  id=\"nhdaHnfa12-1\"\n  subject={[[]]}\n  why=\"UTC does not change with a change in langitude: it's always the same. This is because china has a single time zone. As such this answer can't be considered correct.\"\n>\n  Standard Time\n</Option>\n\n  <Explanation>\n    This question is basically trying to see if you understand that UTC is a global time\n    that does not change with your position in the globe. 1500 UTC in China is 1500 UTC in great britain,\n    independent of the local time and time zone that is observed.\n\n    This means that if you are at a position where sunrise was observed at 18:00 UTC, 15 East sunrise\n    was observed at 17:00.\n\n    For all the other options this is either completely false, or not necessarily true.\n\n  </Explanation>\n</Question>\n",

variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Which statement is correct for <Subject /> towards an NDB in an\n    area with constant wind and constant magnetic variation?\n  </Text>\n<Option\n  id=\"ikcfibAw6r-1\"\n  subject={[[\"homing\"]]}\n  why=\"Describes the Homing technique\"\n>\n  The relative bearing of the NDB should be kept at 0\n</Option>\n<Option\n  id=\"ikcfibAw6r-2\"\n  subject={[[\"tracking\"]]}\n  why=\"Describes the Tracking technique\"\n>\n  The Relative Bearing of the NDB should be equal (in magnitude and sign) to the\n  experienced Drift Angle.\n</Option>\n<Option id=\"ikcfibAw6r-3\">\n equal to the QDM.\n</Option>\n\n  <Explanation>\n    Keep in mind this question is not necessarily asking what is the best way to get navigate towards\n    the NDB rather, it wants to test if you know the 2 established procedures **Homing** and **Tracking**.\n\n    A good way to learn the difference between the 2 is learning about Homing and Tracking missiles (the\n    type fighter jets use). A homing missile is a simple design it basically keeps the missile target\n    on \"center\", making no effort to compensate for wind, the target movement or anything else. This\n    is extremely inefficient and will cause the missile to follow a non-optimal path.\n\n    A tracking missile is a bit smarter than that: It continuously calculates the target position and\n    it's position and where the 2 will meet, so that any given time a missile is flying the optimal\n    path to its target.\n\n    Dropping out of Top Gun:\n\n    *   When **homing** you keep the ADF marking 0. The goal here is to get to the target for sure,\n        regardless of the convoluted path you take there.\n    *   When **tracking** you take into account the wind and correct for that by applying a Correction\n        equal to the drift angle. This relies on you having access to precise drift angle information.\n\n  </Explanation>\n</Question>\n",

On\nthe other hand, a DME station is only to process 2700 PPPS.\n\nIf we assume that 95% of the aircraft are in the vicinity of a DME are in\ntracking mode, and the remaining 5% are in search mode, we can conclude that the\nDME will be saturated at 100 aircraft (`95 x 25 + 5 x 150 = 2650`). Keep in mind\nthis is not a precise value. If all aircraft are in search mode, the DME is\nsaturated the DME is saturated at 18 aircraft. If all aircraft are not doing\nthat many interrogations, one DME can satisfy the needs of hundreds of\ninterrogators.     "text": "\n# ILS Principles\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **062.02.05.01.01** -- Name the three main components of an ILS: the\n    localiser (LOC); the glide path (GP); range information (markers or DME).\n2.  **062.02.05.01.02** -- State the site locations of the ILS components: the\n    LOC antenna should be located on the extension of the runway centre line at\n    the stop-end; the GP antenna should be locate beyond the runway threshold,\n    laterally displaced to the side of the runway centre line.\n3.  **062.02.05.01.03** -- Explain that marker beacons produce radiation\n    patterns to indicate predetermined distances from the threshold along the\n    ILS GP.\n4.  **062.02.05.01.04** -- State that marker beacons are sometimes replaced by a\n    DME paired with the LOC frequency.\n5.  **062.02.05.01.05** -- State that in the ILS LOC frequency assigned band\n    108.0-111.975 MHz, only frequencies which have an odd number in the first\n    decimal are ILS LOC frequencies.\n6.  **062.02.05.01.06** -- State that the GP operates in the UHF band.\n7.  **062.02.05.01.07** -- Describe the use of the 90-Hz and the 150-Hz signals\n    in the LOC and GP transmitters/receivers, stating how the signals at the\n    receivers vary with angular deviation.\n8.  **062.02.05.01.08** -- State that the UHF GP frequency is selected\n    automatically by being paired with the LOC frequency.\n9.  **062.02.05.01.09** -- Explain that both the LOC and the GP antenna radiates\n    side lobes (false beams) which can give rise to false centre-line and false\n    GP indication.\n10. **062.02.05.01.10** -- Explain that the back beam from the LOC antenna may\n    be used as a published \"non-precision approach\".\n11. **062.02.05.01.11** -- State that the recommended GP is 3 degrees .\n12. **062.02.05.01.12** -- Name the frequency, modulation and identification\n    assigned to all marker beacons. All marker beacons operate on 75-MHz carrier\n    frequency. The modulation frequencies of the audio are:\n    - outer marker: low;\n    - middle marker: medium;\n    - inner marker: high. The audio frequency modulation (for identification) is\n      the continuous modulation of the audio frequency and is keyed as follows:\n    - outer marker: 2 dashes per second continuously;\n    - middle marker: a continuous series of alternate dots and dashes;\n    - inner marker: 6 dots per second continuously.\n    - The outer-marker cockpit indicator is coloured blue,\n    - The middle marker amber, and\n    - The inner marker white.\n13. **062.02.05.01.13** -- State that the final-approach area contains a fix or\n    facility that permits verification of the ILS GP-altimeter relationship. The\n    outer marker or DME is usually used for this purpose.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ |     "text": "\n# Modes and codes\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **062.03.04.02.01** -- State that the interrogator transmits its\n    interrogations in the form of a series of pulse pairs.\n2.  **062.03.04.02.02** -- Name the interrogation modes: Mode A; Mode C; Mode S.\n3.  **062.03.04.02.03** -- State that the interrogation frequency and the reply\n    frequency are different.\n4.  **062.03.04.02.04** -- Explain that the decoding of the time interval\n    between the pulse pairs determines the operating mode of the transponder:\n    Mode A: transmission of aircraft transponder code; Mode C: transmission of\n    aircraft pressure altitude; Mode S: selection of aircraft address and\n    transmission of flight data for the ground surveillance.\n5.  **062.03.04.02.05** -- State that Mode A designation is a sequence of four\n    digits which can be manually selected from 4 096 available codes.\n6.  **062.03.04.02.06** -- State that in Mode C reply, the pressure altitude is\n    reported in 100-ft increments.\n7.  **062.03.04.02.07** -- State that in addition to the information provided,\n    on request from ATC, a special position identification (SPI) pulse can be\n    transmitted but only as a result of a manual selection by the pilot (IDENT\n    button).\n8.  **062.03.04.02.08** -- State the need for compatibility of Mode S with Mode\n    A and C.\n9.  **062.03.04.02.09** -- Explain that Mode S transponders receive\n    interrogations from TCAS and SSR ground stations.\n10. **062.03.04.02.10** -- State that Mode S interrogation contains either the\n    aircraft address, selective call or all-call address.\n11. **062.03.04.02.11** -- State that every aircraft is allocated an ICAO\n    aircraft address, which is hard-coded into the Mode S control segment; user segment.\n4.  **062.06.01.02.04** -- State that each satellite broadcasts ranging signals\n    on two UHF frequencies: L1 and L2.\n5.  **062.06.01.02.05** -- State that SPS is a positioning and timing service\n    provided on frequency L1.\n6.  **062.06.01.02.06** -- State that PPS uses both frequencies L1 and L2.\n7.  **062.06.01.02.07** -- State that the satellites transmit a coded signal\n    used for ranging, identification (satellite individual PRN code), timing and\n    navigation.\n8.  **062.06.01.02.08** -- State that the navigation message contains:\n\n- satellite clock correction parameters;\n- Universal Time Coordinated (UTC) parameters;\n- an ionospheric model;\n- satellite health data.\n\n9.  **062.06.01.02.09** -- State that an ionospheric model is used to calculate\n    the time delay of the signal travelling through the ionosphere.\n10. **062.06.01.02.10** -- State that two codes are transmitted on the L1\n    frequency, namely a coarse acquisition (C/A) code and a precision (P) code.\n    The P code is not used for standard positioning service (SPS).\n11. **062.06.01.02.11** -- State that satellites are equipped with atomic clocks\n    which allow the system to keep very accurate time reference.\n12. **062.06.01.02.12** -- State that the control segment comprises: a master\n    control station; a ground antenna; monitoring stations.\n13. **062.06.01.02.13** -- State that the control segment provides: monitoring\n    of the constellation status; correction of orbital parameters; navigation\n    data uploading.\n14. **062.06.01.02.14** -- State that GNSS supplies three-dimensional position\n    fixes and speed data, plus a precise time reference.\n15. **062.06.01.02.15** -- State that a GNSS receiver is able to determine the\n    distance to a satellite by determining the difference between the time of\n    transmission by the satellite and the time of reception.\n16. **062.06.01.02.16** -- State that the initial distance calculated to the\n    satellites is called pseudo-range because the difference between the GNSS\n    receiver and the satellite time references initially creates an erroneous\n    range.\n17. **062.06.01.02.17** -- State that each range defines a sphere with its\n    centre at the satellite.\n18. **062.06.01.02.18** -- State that there are four unknown parameters (x, y, z\n    and Delta t) (receiver clock error) which require the measurement of ranges\n    to four different satellites in order to get the position.\n19. **062.06.01.02.19** -- State that the GNSS receiver is able to synchronise\n    to the correct time reference when receiving four satellites.\n20. **062.06.01.02.20** -- State that the receiver is able to calculate aircraft\n    ground speed using the space vehicle (SV) Doppler frequency shift or the\n    change in receiver position over time.\n21. **062.06.01.02.21** -- Define \"receiver autonomous integrity monitoring\n    (RAIM)\" as a technique that ensures the integrity of the provided data by\n    redundant measurements.\n22. **062.06.01.02.22** -- State that RAIM is achieved by consistency checks\n    among range measurements.\n23. **062.06.01.02.23** -- State that basic RAIM requires five satellites.
