  "062.06.01.03": {
    "id": "062.06.01.03",
    "text": "\n# Errors and factors affecting accuracy\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **062.06.01.03.01** -- List the most significant factors that affect\n    accuracy:\n    - ionospheric propagation delay;\n    - dilution of precision;\n    - satellite clock error;\n    - satellite orbital variations;\n    - multipath effects.\n2.  **062.06.01.03.02** -- State that a user equivalent range error (UERE) can\n    be computed from all these factors.\n3.  **062.06.01.03.03** -- State that the error from the ionospheric propagation\n    delay (IPD) can be reduced by modelling, using a model of the ionosphere, or\n    can almost be eliminated by using two frequencies.\n4.  **062.06.01.03.04** -- State that ionospheric delay is the most significant\n    error.\n5.  **062.06.01.03.05** -- State that dilution of precision arises from the\n    geometry and number of satellites in view. It is called geometric dilution\n    of precision (GDOP).\n6.  **062.06.01.03.06** -- State that the UERE in combination with the geometric\n    dilution of precision (GDOP) allows for an estimation of position accuracy.\n7.  **062.06.01.03.07** -- State that errors in the satellite orbits are due to:\n    solar winds; gravitation of the Sun and the Moon.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 062.06.01.03.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      | X   | X       |\n| 062.06.01.03.02 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      | X   |         |\n| 062.06.01.03.03 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      | X   |         |\n| 062.06.01.03.04 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      | X   |         |\n| 062.06.01.03.05 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      | X   |         |\n| 062.06.01.03.06 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      | X   |         |\n| 062.06.01.03.07 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      | X   |         |\n\n## Summary\n\n### Ionospheric propagation delay\n\n### Dilution of precision\n\nGPS systems are based on the principle of triangulation, that is, the\ndetermination of a position based on the distance from a set of know positions.\nThe quality of this determination is directly proportional to the position of\nthe satellites. If the satellites are closely positioned the quality of the\n\"triangulation\" will be significantly poorer than if you have a set of\nsatellites that are well separated.\n\n### Satellite clock error\n\nThe satellite atomic clock can and will experience noise and clock drift errors.\nThis error can be measured by comparing the atomic clock reading with ground\natomic clocks. The clock error is sent to receivers as part of the navigation\nmessage.\n\nTogether with satellite orbital variations, clock errors are known as \"Ephemeris\nerrors\".\n\n### Satellite orbital variations\n\nSatellite position is subject to error caused by gravitational forces of\ncelestial bodies, solar winds, among others. The precise position of a satellite\nis checked every 12 hours and the up to date position error is sent to receivers\nas part of the navigation message.\n\nTogether With clock errors, orbital variation errors are known as \"Ephemeris\nerrors\".\n\n### Multipath Effects\n\nGPS signals can reflect off terrain and buildings arriving at the receiver with\ndelays. Multipath errors due to long bounces, are easy to identify and discard.\nErrors from small bounces are significantly harder, but can be minimized by\nusing specialized antennas that better measure the \"direction\" of the incoming\nsignal and split bounced signals based on their incoming direction.\n\n<Question id=\"QJ03TX610J\" lo={[\"062.06.01.03.01\"]} contentRef=\"## Summary\">\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Which of the following is a source error that affects the accuracy and\n    reliability of GPS systems\n  </Text>\n<Text variant=\"oneTwo\">\n  Which of the following are a source error that affects the accuracy and\n  reliability of GPS systems\n</Text>\n<Text variant=\"multipleCorrect\" select={5}>\n  Which of the following are a source error that affects the accuracy and\n  reliability of GPS systems\n</Text>\n<Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n  One of the more significant errors that reduces the accuracy of the GNSS\n  signal-in-space is ...\n</Text>\n<Option correct why=\"Satellite atomic clocks drift leading to errors\">\n  Satellite clock\n</Option>\n<Option\n  correct\n  why=\"Satellite orbits change slightly due to gravitational effects and solar winds leading to errors\"\n>\n  Satellite Ephemeris\n</Option>\n<Option correct why=\"Describes the source of errors of Satellite Ephemeris\">\n  Solar winds and gravitation of the sun, moon, and planets\n</Option>\n<Option correct why=\"A tight clustering causes dilution of precision errors\">\n  Tight Clustering of satellites\n</Option>\n<Option correct why=\"Causes ionospheric propagation delay\">\n  Atmospheric Propagation\n</Option>\n<Option correct why=\"Describes multipath effects\">\n  Reflection of satellite signals from terrain\n</Option>\n<Option correct>\n  dilution of precision caused by the relative positions of the navigation\n  satellites.\n</Option>\n<Option why=\"The existence of a Satellite -     "text": "\n# Performance-based navigation (PBN) principles\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **062.07.04.01.01** -- Define \"path definition error\" (PDE).\n2.  **062.07.04.01.02** -- Define \"flight technical error\" (FTE) and state that\n    the FTE is the error in following the prescribed path, either by the\n    auto-flight system or by the pilot.\n3.  **062.07.04.01.03** -- Define \"navigation system error\" (NSE) and state that\n    the accuracy of a navigation system may be referred to as NSE.\n4.  **062.07.04.01.04** -- Define \"total system error\" (TSE) and state that the\n    geometric sum of the PDE, FTE and NSE equals the TSE.\n5.  **062.07.04.01.05** -- State that navigation accuracy depends on the TSE.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 062.07.04.01.01 | X       |        | X          |             |        | X   | X       |\n| 062.07.04.01.02 | X       |        | X          |             |        | X   | X       |\n| 062.07.04.01.03 | X       |        | X          |             |        | X   | X       |\n| 062.07.04.01.04 | X       |        | X          |             |        | X   | X       |\n| 062.07.04.01.05 | X       |        | X          |             |        | X   |         |\n\n## Summary\n\n### PBN errors\n\n- **Path Definition Error (PDE)**: Corresponds to an error between the RNAV path\n  and the path over the ground. This error arises from the RNAV system inability\n  to accurately define the desired path. **If you were a RNAV system**, this\n  error would be equivalent to you drawing a line in a chart that is not 100%\n  aligned with the optimal path between 2 waypoints.\n\n- **Flight Technical Error (FTE)**: Corresponds to an error between the aircraft\n  flight path and the RNAV path. This error arises from the piloting performance\n  of the aircraft or the autopilot system. This error is the difference between\n  your actual flight path, and the line you drew on the chart before.\n\n- **Navigation System Error (NSE)**: Corresponds to an error between the actual\n  position of the aircraft and the position reported measured by the aircraft\n  systems.\n\n- **Total System Error (TSE)**: Is the sum of the 3 errors described above.\n\n<Question\n  id=\"C6QGC3RVJS\"\n  lo={[\n  \"062.07.04.01.01\",\n  \"062.07.04.01.02\",\n  \"062.07.04.01.03\",\n  \"062.07.04.01.04\",\n  ]}\n  contentRef=\"### PBN errors\"\n>\n  <Text variant=\"oneCorrect\">\n    Which of these errors constitutes a <Subject />?\n  </Text>\n<Option subject={[[\"Path Definition Error\"], [\"PDE\"]]}>\n  An error during PBN operations rising from the RNAV system and its inability\n  to specify the desired path.\n</Option>\n<Option subject={[[\"Flight Technical Error\"], [\"FTE\"]]}>\n  An error during PBN operations related to the execution of flight along a\n  defined path.\n</Option>\n<Option subject={[[\"Navigation System Error\"], [\"NSE\"]]}>\n  An error during PBN operation in the accuracy of determining the actual\n  aircraft coordinates.\n</Option>\n<Option subject={[[\"Total System Error\"], [\"TSE\"]]}>\n  The combined sum of Path Defintion, Flight Technical, and Navigation system\n  errors.\n</Option>\n<Option subject={[[\"Total System Error\"], [\"TSE\"]]}>PDE + FTE + NSE.</Option>\n<Option why=\"Almost describes TSE, except TSE is the sum of the 3 errors: PDE + TSE + NSE\">\n  PDE + FTE - NSE\n</Option>\n<Option why=\"Almost describes TSE, except TSE is the sum of the 3 errors: PDE + TSE + NSE\">\n  PDE + FTE / NSE\n</Option>\n\n  <Option why=\"Almost describes TSE, except TSE is the sum of the 3 errors: PDE + TSE + NSE\">\n    PDE + FTE x NSE\n  </Option>\n</Question>\n",

    "text": "\n# North Atlantic High Level Airspace (NAT HLA)\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **071.01.03.03.01** -- State the lateral dimensions (in general terms) and\n    vertical limits of the NAT HLA.\n2.  **071.01.03.03.02** -- Define the following acronyms: LRNS, MASPS, NAT HLA,\n    OCA, OTS, PRM, RVSM, SLOP, and WATRS.\n3.  **071.01.03.03.03** -- State the NAT HLA operations.\n4.  **071.01.03.03.04** -- Describe the routes for aircraft with only one\n    long-range navigation system (LRNS).\n5.  **071.01.03.03.05** -- Describe the routes for aircraft with short-range\n    navigation equipment only.\n6.  **071.01.03.03.06** -- Explain why the horizontal (i.e. latitudinal and\n    longitudinal) and vertical navigation performance of operators within NAT\n    HLA is monitored on a continual basis.\n7.  **071.01.03.03.07** -- Describe the organised track system (OTS).\n8.  **071.01.03.03.08** -- State the OTS changeover periods.\n9.  **071.01.03.03.09** -- Describe the NAT track message.\n10. **071.01.03.03.10** -- Illustrate routes between northern Europe and the\n    Spain/Canaries/Lisbon flight information region (FIR) within NAT HLA.\n11. **071.01.03.03.11** -- Describe the function of the North American Routes\n    (NARs) and Shannon Oceanic Transition Area (SOTA) and Northern Oceanic\n    Transition Area (NOTA).\n12. **071.01.03.03.12** -- State that all flights should plan to operate on\n    great-circle tracks joining successive significant waypoints.\n13. **071.01.03.03.13** -- State that during the hours of validity of the OTS,\n    operators are encouraged to plan flights: in accordance with the OTS; or\n    along a route to join or leave an outer track of the OTS; or on a random\n    route to remain clear of the OTS, either laterally or vertically.\n14. **071.01.03.03.14** -- State which flight levels are available on OTS tracks\n    during OTS periods.\n15. **071.01.03.03.15** -- State which flight levels are to be planned on random\n    tracks or outside OTS periods.\n16. **071.01.03.03.16** -- Selection of cruising altitude. Specify the\n    appropriate cruising levels for normal long-range IFR flights and for those\n    operating on the North Atlantic OTS.\n17. **071.01.03.03.17** -- Intentionally left blank\n18. **071.01.03.03.18** -- State that pilots should notify the oceanic area\n    control centre (OAC) of the maximum acceptable flight level possible at the\n    boundary.\n19. **071.01.03.03.19** -- State that at some aerodromes which are situated\n    close to oceanic boundaries, the oceanic clearance must be obtained before\n    departure.\n20. **071.01.03.03.20** -- State that if an aircraft encounters, whilst en-route\n    to the NAT Oceanic Airspace, an in-flight equipment failure relevant to the\n    airspace, then the pilot must advise ATC when requesting oceanic clearance.\n21. **071.01.03.03.21** -- State that after obtaining and reading back the\n    clearance, the pilot should monitor the forward estimate for oceanic entry,\n    and if this changes by 3 minutes or more, unless providing position reports\n    via automatic dependent surveillance - contract (ADS-C), the pilot must pass\n    a revised estimate on to ATC.\n22. **071.01.03.03.22** -- State that pilots should pay particular attention\n    when the issued clearance differs from the flight plan as a significant\n    proportion of navigation errors investigated in the NAT Region involve\n    aircraft which have followed their flight plan rather than the differing\n    clearance.\n23. **071.01.03.03.23** -- State that if the entry point of the oceanic route\n    for which the flight is cleared differs from that originally requested or\n    the oceanic flight level differs from the current flight level, the pilot is\n    responsible for requesting and obtaining the necessary domestic\n    re-clearance.\n24. **071.01.03.03.24** -- State that there are three elements to an oceanic\n    clearance: route, speed, and flight level, and that these elements serve to\n    provide for the three basic elements of separation: lateral, longitudinal,\n    and vertical.\n25. **071.01.03.03.25** -- Communications and position-reporting procedures\n    State that pilots communicate with OACCs via aeradio stations staffed by\n    communicators who have no executive ATC authority.\n26. **071.01.03.03.26** -- State that messages are relayed from the ground\n    station to the air traffic controllers of the relevant OACC for action.\n27. **071.01.03.03.27** -- State that frequencies from the lower HF bands tend\n    to be used for communications during night-time and those from the higher\n    bands during daytime. When initiating contact with an aeradio station, the\n    pilot should state the HF frequency in use.\n28. **071.01.03.03.28** -- State that since oceanic traffic typically\n    communicates with ATC through aeradio facilities, a satellite communication\n    (SATVOICE) call, made due to unforeseen inability to communicate by other\n    means, should be made to such a facility rather than the ATC centre, unless\n    the urgency of the communication dictates otherwise.\n29. **071.01.03.03.29** -- State that an air-to-air VHF frequency has been\n    established for worldwide use when aircraft are out of range of VHF ground\n    stations which utilise the same or adjacent frequencies. This frequency,\n    123.450 MHz, is intended for pilot-to-pilot exchanges of operationally\n    significant information.\n30. **071.01.03.03.30** -- State that any pilot, who provides position reports\n    via data link and encounters significant meteorological phenomena (such as\n    moderate/severe turbulence or icing, volcanic ash or thunderstorms), should\n    report this information.\n31. **071.01.03.03.31** -- State that all turbine-engined aeroplanes having a\n    maximum certified take-off mass exceeding 5 700 kg or authorised to carry\n    more than 19 passengers are required to carry and operate airborne collision\n    avoidance system (ACAS) II in the NAT Region.\n32. **071.01.03.03.32** -- State that even with the growing use of data-link\n    communications, a significant volume of NAT airground communications are\n    conducted using voice on single sideband (SSB) HF frequencies. To support\n    airground ATC communications in the North Atlantic Region, 24 HF\n    frequencies have been allocated, in bands ranging from 2.8 to 18 MHz.\n33. **071.01.03.03.33** -- Application of the Mach number technique (NAT HLA)\n    State that practical experience has shown that when two or more turbojet\n    aircraft, operating along the same route at the same flight level, maintain\n    the same Mach number, they are more likely to maintain a constant time\n    interval between each other than when using other methods.\n34. **071.01.03.03.34** -- State that after leaving oceanic airspace, pilots\n    must maintain their assigned Mach number in domestic controlled airspace\n    unless and until the appropriate ATC unit authorises a change.\n35. **071.01.03.03.35** -- NAT HLA flight operation and navigation procedures\n    State that the pre-flight procedures for any NAT HLA flight must include a\n    Universal Time Coordinated (UTC) time check.\n36. **071.01.03.03.36** -- Describe the function and use of the master document.\n37. **071.01.03.03.37** -- State the requirements for position plotting.\n38. **071.01.03.03.38** -- Describe the pre-flight procedures for: the alignment\n    of IRS; the satellite navigation availability prediction programme for\n    flights using global navigation satellite long-range navigation system (GNSS\n    LRNS); loading of initial waypoints; and flight plan check.\n39. **071.01.03.03.39** -- Describe the strategic lateral offset procedure\n    (SLOP) and state that along a route or track there will be three positions\n    that an aircraft may fly: centre line, or up to 2 NM right.\n40. **071.01.03.03.40** -- State that RNAV 10 retains the RNP 10 designation, as\n    specified in the Performance-based Navigation Manual (ICAO Doc 9613. (ICAO\n    Doc 7030, NAT Chapter 4..\n41. **071.01.03.03.41** -- State that both aircraft and operators must be RNP\n    10- or RNP 4-approved by the State of the Operator or the State of Registry,\n    as appropriate.\n42. **071.01.03.03.42** -- State that RNP 10 is the minimum navigation\n    specification for the application of 93 km (50 NM) lateral separation.\n43. **071.01.03.03.43** -- Reduced vertical separation minima (RVSM) flight in\n    NAT HLA State the altimeter cross-check to be performed before entering NAT\n    HLA.\n44. **071.01.03.03.44** -- State the altimeter cross-check to be performed when\n    entering and flying in NAT HLA.\n45. **071.01.03.03.45** -- State that pilots not using controllerpilot\n    data-link communications (CPDLC)/ADS-C always report to ATC immediately on\n    leaving the current cruising level and on reaching any new cruising level.\n46. **071.01.03.03.46** -- State that flight crew should report when a 300-ft\n    deviation or more occurs.\n47. **071.01.03.03.47** -- Navigation planning procedures List the factors to be\n    considered by the commander before commencing the flight.\n48. **071.01.03.03.48** -- For this part, state that the\n    general concept of these NAT in-flight contingency procedures is, whenever\n    operationally feasible, to offset the assigned route by 5 NM and climb or\n    descend to a level which differs from those normally used by 500 ft if below\n    FL 410 or by 1 000 ft if above FL 410.\n50. **071.01.03.03.50** -- State all the factors which may affect the direction\n    of turn including: direction to an alternate aerodrome; terrain clearance;\n    levels allocated on adjacent routes or tracks and any known SLOP offsets\n    adopted by other nearby traffic.\n51.     "id": "071.02.02.02",
    "text": "\n# Procedure to apply in case of performance deterioration, on ground/in flight\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **071.02.02.02.01** -- Explain that the effects of icing are wide-ranging,\n    unpredictable and dependent upon individual aircraft design. The magnitude\n    of these effects is dependent upon many variables, but the effects can be\n    both significant and dangerous.\n2.  **071.02.02.02.02** -- Explain that in icing conditions, for a given speed\n    and a given angle of attack, wing lift can be reduced by as much as 30 % and\n    drag increased by up to 40 %. State that these changes in lift and drag will\n    significantly increase stall speed, reduce controllability, and alter flight\n    characteristics.\n3.  **071.02.02.02.03** -- Explain that ice on critical surfaces and on the\n    airframe may also break away during take-off and be ingested into engines,\n    possibly damaging fan and compressor blades.\n4.  **071.02.02.02.04** -- Explain that ice forming on pitot tubes and static\n    ports or on angle-of-attack vanes may give false altitude, airspeed,\n    angle-of-attack and engine-power information for air-data systems.\n5.  **071.02.02.02.05** -- Explain that ice, frost and snow formed on the\n    critical surfaces on the ground can have a totally different effect on\n    aircraft flight characteristics than ice, frost and snow formed in flight.\n6.  **071.02.02.02.06** -- Explain that flight in known icing conditions is\n    subject to limitations that are contained in Part B of the operations\n    manual.\n7.  **071.02.02.02.07** -- Explain where procedures and performances regarding\n    flight in expected or actual icing conditions can be found.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 071.02.02.02.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 071.02.02.02.02 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 071.02.02.02.03 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 071.02.02.02.04 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 071.02.02.02.05 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 071.02.02.02.06 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 071.02.02.02.07 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n",
